  "response_text": "The Gini coefficient tracks the inequality in livestock health across households across timesteps. In homogeneous settings (homog-behav-types? = True), the dark orange line representing E-RO (baseline) agents exhibits a sharply rising Gini value, peaking sharply at ~step 40 with the value of ~0.09 before leveling off. This matches E-RO agents' risk-averse strategy; their reliance on historical data and aversion to climate uncertainty likely causes herd fragmentation early as agents reduce grazing aggressively to avoid losses, leading to divergent herd health trajectories across households.   \\n\nE-LBD (brown line), with learning-by-doing, shows slower inequality accumulation. The Gini rises more gradually, peaking around step 60 at ~0.075. This reflects E-LBD agents' adaptive behavior: modest stocking adjustments based on personal experience of livestock survival help mitigate divergence, stabilizing outcomes. In contrast, E-RO-SL1 (grey line) shows the lowest inequality (~0.035 peak at step 40), as constrained social learning (through knowledge-radius 1) allows agents to observe neighbors’ strategies and converge toward shared livestock decisions. However, homog-behav-types? = True makes these simulations unlikely in the provided parameters, suggesting either parameter shifts or parallel runs.   \\n\nKey stops at ~step 40-60 mark divergence thresholds; beyond these, E-RO and E-LBD maintain elevated inequality, while E-RO-SL1 remains stable, indicating evolutionary divergence in decision-making mechanisms under climatic variability. Livestock health equality naturally deteriorates without social intervention, aligning with the model’s climate-stress paradigm primarily affecting agents lacking collective coordination mechanisms.   }"
